{"questionId":"8113","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>Figure 3</strong> illustrates the market for cotton in the country of San Marcus, a small closed economy. Cotton is used as an input in the San Marcus textile industry. Quantity is in thousands of kilograms (kg).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img style=\"float:left;\" src=\"__IMG__/75a7200605d60c433d073aa8afff615397bc56d9.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Government of San Marcus decides to provide a subsidy equal to $8 per kilogram to its producers of cotton.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the change in the consumer surplus resulting from the subsidy.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\left( {50 + 75} \\right)}}{2} \\times \\left( {10 - 5} \\right) + 1000\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>50</mn>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>75</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>10</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1000</mn>\n</math></span><br><br><em><strong>OR</strong></em></p>\n<p>(0.5 × 75 × 15) − (0.5 × 50 × 10) =&nbsp;562.5 − 250</p>\n<p><em>Any valid working is sufficient for <strong>[1]</strong></em>.</p>\n<p><em>Valid working <strong>may</strong> be</em>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>correct workings for initial CS (0.5 × 50 × 10)</li>\n<li>correct workings for final CS (0.5 × 75 × 15)</li>\n<li>correct workings for the trapezium <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\left( {50 + 75} \\right)}}{2} \\times \\left( {10 - 5} \\right) + 1000\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>50</mn>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>75</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>10</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1000</mn>\n</math></span>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>= $312 500</p>\n<p><em>An answer of 312 500 or $312 500 (without working) is sufficient for <strong>[1]</strong></em>.</p>\n<p><em>OFR may apply</em>.</p>","meta":{"questionId":"8113","referenceCode":"18N.3.HL.TZ0.2b.iv","subjectId":"48-dp-economics","title":"Calculate the change in the consumer surplus resulting from the subsidy.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.iv","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["First exams 2022","Last exams 2021","Last exams 2021","Section 1: Microeconomics","First exams 2022","Unit 2: Microeconomics","2.7 Role of government in microeconomics","2.7.2 Main forms of government intervention in markets","First exams 2022","Unit 2: Microeconomics","2.3 Competitive market equilibrium","2.3.4 Consumer and producer surplus","First exams 2022","Unit 2: Microeconomics","2.3 Competitive market equilibrium","First exams 2022","Unit 2: Microeconomics","2.7 Role of government in microeconomics","First exams 2022","Unit 2: Microeconomics","Last exams 2021","Section 1: Microeconomics","1.1 Competitive markets: Demand and supply","Market efficiency","Consumer surplus","Last exams 2021","Section 1: Microeconomics","1.1 Competitive markets: Demand and supply","Market efficiency","Last exams 2021","Section 1: Microeconomics","1.1 Competitive markets: Demand and supply"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}